--- Section 3.6. SCHC Port Numbers and protocol number as identifiers
+++ Section 3.6. SCHC Port Numbers and protocol number as identifiers
@@ -341,11 +341,12 @@
-3.6.  SCHC Port Numbers and protocol number as identifiers
-
-   In the current SCHC architecture, the SCHC Stratum Header adds
-   signalling information to the SCHC datagram.  It may be fully
-   compressed, and it does not add any overhead in that case.  The SCHC
-   Stratum Header helps to identify the use of SCHC and selects the
-   correct instance and SoR in the SCHC process.  The SCHC Stratum
-   Header format includes an identifier that depends on the compressed
-   stack layer.  These identifiers are the protocol number at layer
-   three and port numbers at layer four.
+3.6.  SCHC Port Numbers and protocol number as identifiers
+
+   In the SCHC architecture [schc-architecture], a Discriminator is used
+   by the Dispatcher to route incoming SCHC Datagrams to the correct Instance.
+   This Discriminator is derived from the protocol stack layer where SCHC is
+   applied.  Specifically, the IP Protocol Number at Layer 3 and the Port
+   Numbers at Layer 4 serve as the outer Discriminator to signal that the packet
+   carries a SCHC Datagram.  The Dispatcher uses this Discriminator, along with
+   any lower-layer context (such as addresses or ports), to select the correct
+   Instance and its associated Context (which contains the Set of Rules (SoR)).
+   Additionally, if lower-layer context is insufficient to route the packet, an
+   optional Control Header may be added to the SCHC Datagram to carry additional
+   signaling information, such as Session or Instance identifiers.

